# 5 node x 5 node example of a locally-synchronous Game of Life using a logic circuit implementation.
#
# Each repeating block represents a single Game of Life cell.
# The cell consists of:
#   1) A core loop in the center of the block that holds
#      the state of the cell (0 for dead; 1 for alive),
#   2) An outer loop that transmits a copy of the cell's
#      current state to each of its neighbors, and
#   3) A ring-shaped block of logic that decides what
#      the core loop's next state should be based on
#      the values of the cell's neighbors.
#
# At the beginning of each generation update cycle, the core
# loop signal is duplicated and sent to a) the outer loop for
# transmission, and b) back to the core loop for storage and
# computation of the next cycle state. The split signal runs
# clockwise around the outer ring starting from the top. At
# each border with another cell, a copy of the state signal
# is created and waits until a matching signal is received
# from the neighbor (this is done with synch gates). This
# synchronization ensures that no cell can update more than
# one step ahead of its neighbors.
#
# Once the neighbor's signal is received, it is fed into the
# logic ring. A series of logic gates in the logic ring
# determines what the cell's next state should be. The final
# computation is fed into the core loop, replacing the
# previous value, and the cycle begins again.
#
# The outermost layer of green cells are a border condition
# that continuously produces a 0 state.
#
# Each game of life generation takes roughly 800-1600 seconds (in-simulation) to compute.
#
# In this example, we watch a "toad" (2-period oscillating pattern)
# flip back and forth approximately 5 times, for a total of ~10 generations.
